## Environments & Deployment

We use [GitHub Flow](https://docs.github.com/en/get-started/using-github/github-flow): one long-lived branch (`main`), short-lived branches per issue, a Vercel preview deployment (with its own Neon database branch) per PR, and production deploys on merge to `main`. **There is no `staging` branch.** If you need a shared environment for QA or stakeholder review, use a Vercel preview alias ‚Äî never a long-lived branch (see Hard Rule #3).

| Environment | Branch / Source | URL | Database |
|---|---|---|---|
| Development | Local checkout | `http://localhost:3000` | Neon dev branch |
| Preview (per PR) | Open PR against `main` | `<project>-<pr>.vercel.app` | Neon preview branch (auto-created per PR) |
| Production | `main` | `TODO: your-domain.com` | Neon `main` branch |

**Deploy flow:** issue ‚Üí branch from `main` (`<type>/<N>-<slug>`) ‚Üí PR to `main` ‚Üí CI + Vercel preview ‚Üí smoke-test the preview ‚Üí squash-merge ‚Üí production auto-deploys

**Vercel region:** `TODO: your-region` (set in `vercel.json`)

> **Merge UI gotcha:** always use **squash merge**, never "Rebase and merge". GitHub's rebase merge rewrites commit SHAs at merge time. With a single long-lived branch this is harmless, but it's the landmine that makes any two-tier branch flow drift.

## Hard Rules

1. **Australian spelling throughout** ‚Äî favour, colour, organisation, behaviour, licence (noun). Applies to all prose, comments, and string literals.

2. **Issue before branch** ‚Äî every change starts as a GitHub issue, even one-line fixes. Branch names must encode the issue number: `<type>/<issue-number>-<slug>` where `<type>` is one of `feat`, `fix`, `chore`, `docs`. Example: `feat/42-user-profile`. The commit footer references the issue (`Refs: #42`) and the PR body uses `Closes #42`. No exceptions ‚Äî including for hotfixes.

3. **One long-lived branch (`main`)** ‚Äî use GitHub Flow. Never create a `staging`, `develop`, or `release/*` long-lived branch. If you need a shared environment for QA, use a Vercel preview alias. Long-lived secondary branches drift on every merge because GitHub's rebase-merge rewrites commit SHAs.

4. **Squash-merge PRs to `main`** ‚Äî never use "Rebase and merge" or "Create a merge commit" in the GitHub UI. Squash merge keeps `main` linear and audit-friendly, and avoids the SHA-rewrite drift that breaks two-tier flows.

5. **Plan before code** ‚Äî always use the plan ‚Üí approve ‚Üí execute pattern. Never write code without an approved plan. Never skip the plan step.

6. **Spec-driven development** ‚Äî every feature starts as a spec document in `docs/specs/` before any code is written. Specs are committed to the repo.

7. **Expand-migrate-contract for schema changes** ‚Äî never ship a destructive schema change (column drop, rename, type change, NOT NULL on existing data) in a single PR. Split it across deploys:

   1. **Expand:** add the new column/table alongside the old one. Deploy. Both old and new code paths work.
   2. **Migrate:** backfill data into the new shape. Switch reads and writes to the new column. Deploy.
   3. **Contract:** drop the old column once nothing references it. Deploy.

   *Why:* Vercel rolling deploys run old and new code concurrently for ~30 seconds during a release. A single-PR rename means the old containers query a column that no longer exists and start serving 500s mid-deploy.

   *Concrete example ‚Äî renaming `users.email` to `users.email_address`:*
   - **PR 1 (expand):** add `email_address` column nullable, write to both `email` and `email_address`, read from `email`.
   - **PR 2 (migrate):** backfill `email_address` from `email`, switch reads to `email_address`, drop the dual-write.
   - **PR 3 (contract):** drop the `email` column.

   For pure additive changes (new column, new table, new index) you can ship all three steps in one PR ‚Äî the rule only kicks in when something is being removed, renamed, or made stricter.

   **Pre-launch corollary:** while you have no real users and the dev DB is fully reseedable, drop the ceremony ‚Äî reseed freely, rename columns in one PR, do whatever shape changes the design needs. The rule kicks in the moment you have users you can't safely lose. Don't carry pre-launch complexity into post-launch ops, and don't carry post-launch ceremony back into pre-launch iteration.

8. **No `any` types** ‚Äî TypeScript strict mode is non-negotiable. Use proper generics, union types, or `unknown` with type guards. ESLint enforces `no-explicit-any`.

9. **No `console.log`** ‚Äî use the structured logger at `src/lib/logger.ts`. ESLint enforces `no-console`. The logger produces JSON with timestamps and levels.

10. **All API responses use the envelope** ‚Äî `{ success: true, data: T }` or `{ success: false, error: { message, code } }`. Use `ok()`, `created()`, `noContent()`, `handleError()` from `src/lib/api-response.ts`.

11. **Auth via `getAuth()` only** ‚Äî never call `auth()` directly in route handlers. Always use `getAuth()` from `src/lib/auth/get-auth.ts` which handles both Clerk sessions and mobile JWT.

12. **Validate all inputs with Zod** ‚Äî every API endpoint validates request body and query params with Zod schemas. Schemas live in `src/lib/validations/`. Never trust user input.

13. **Rate limit all endpoints** ‚Äî use `checkRateLimit()` from `src/lib/rate-limit.ts`. Public endpoints get `publicRateLimiter`, write operations get `writeRateLimiter`, authenticated requests get `rateLimiter`.

14. **Soft delete, never hard delete** ‚Äî set `status = 'deleted'`, never `DELETE FROM`. All queries should filter out deleted records.

## Labels

Apply at least one `type:*` and one `scope:*` label to every issue and PR. The label taxonomy is created on a fresh repo by `claude-config/scripts/setup-labels.sh`.

| Group | Labels | When to use |
|---|---|---|
| `type:*` | `type:feature`, `type:fix`, `type:chore`, `type:docs` | What kind of change is this? |
| `scope:*` | `scope:api`, `scope:dashboard`, `scope:mobile`, `scope:schema`, `scope:auth`, `scope:workflow` | Which area of the codebase? |
| `vertical:*` | TODO: project-specific (e.g. `vertical:billing`, `vertical:onboarding`) | Optional ‚Äî only if your product has clearly distinct verticals |
| Status | `needs-triage`, `blocked`, `urgent` | Triage state ‚Äî applied as needed |

The `<type>` segment of the branch name (`feat/`, `fix/`, `chore/`, `docs/`) must match the `type:*` label on the issue.

